Patch Set 19:

(7 comments)

Had a call with Tony, most of the ownership changes we can see in Dallas come from the fact that previously fetch-bits.yml was being delegated to the registry_host, which I think is wrong:

1. We execute dci-openshift-agent on the jumphost, which is localhost as far as ansible is concerned
2. We mirror the resources on the jumphost, the idea of having an air-gapped/disconnected environment is that the provisioner (and the OCP cluster) only have access to the jumphost
3. Our inventory entries for the registry_host had defined a remote user (dci-openshift-agent) but the implicit localhost entry does not have a remote user, it runs with whatever user the PID is owned by
4. Our different tools (dci-pipeline, test-runner, etc) do not enforce the d-o-a to run as a certain user, we should fix this

I don't exactly understand how this patch does what you say it does... is it because you're now prefixing the task so it auto-magically uploads at the end?

Patch Set 1:

> Patch Set 1:
> 
> I don't exactly understand how this patch does what you say it does... is it because you're now prefixing the task so it auto-magically uploads at the end?

In fact, yes ;)
Junit plugin works by consuming env variables that are defined before ansible is launched. That's why those env vars are managed by dci-pipeline. The var JUNIT_TEST_CASE_PREFIX considers a task only as test case if it has this value as prefix and it is set to test_ in dci-pipeline

I fear if we try to explain all cases, like how with github, how with openshift, how with elk then the guide will be too complex.
Why not just focusing on one simple case. The simplest one local gerrit + zuul + nodepool + logserver with a local node provider (k1s?).
At the end of the guide it is more likely the reader will have a working platform. Then he can start to add a nodepool provider, ELK but this should not part of this guide IMO.
